<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-06-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-06-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="573" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d573">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Lord <persName type="from">Gough</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Olney</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">British
                                        Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Newport</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-06-07"><hi rend="italic">June 7,
                                1895</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to Mr. Uhl’s note of the
                            18th ultimo, I have the honor to inform you that I am in receipt of a
                            communication from Her Majesty’s principal secretary for foreign
                            affairs, stating that, in accordance with the request of your
                            Government, British naval officers will be authorized to continue
                            sealing up of arms and ammunition of United States sealing vessels if
                            requested to do so.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hugh Gough</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>